Manual for Happinese (Friend edition)

Angel Wang

HappyDB is a corpus of 100,000 crowd-sourced happy moments via Amazon’s Mechanical Turk. You can read more about it on https://arxiv.org/abs/1801.07746.

Here, we explore this data set and try to answer the question, “What makes people happy?”

Load all necessary packages

From the packages’ descriptions:

  • tidyverse is an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures;
  • tidytext allows text mining using ‘dplyr’, ‘ggplot2’, and other tidy tools;
  • DT provides an R interface to the JavaScript library DataTables;
  • scales map data to aesthetics, and provide methods for automatically determining breaks and labels for axes and legends;
  • wordcloud2 provides an HTML5 interface to wordcloud for data visualization;
  • gridExtra contains miscellaneous functions for “grid” graphics;
  • ngram is for constructing n-grams (“tokenizing”), as well as generating new text based on the n-gram structure of a given text input (“babbling”);

Part 1 - Load the processed text data along with demographic information on contributors

First,I process the raw textual data ‘cleaned_hm.csv’ saved in $ data $ file by cleaning data, removing stopwords and creating a tidy version of texts which is saved in $ output $ file.

hm_data <- read_csv("/Users/angelwang/Desktop/fall 2023/4243/ads-fall2023-project1-angelw29/output/processed_moments.csv")

urlfile<-'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rit-public/HappyDB/master/happydb/data/demographic.csv'
demo_data <- read_csv(urlfile)

I choose a subset of the data out of the tidy version of texts and keep the required columns for analysis.

hm_data <- hm_data %>%
  inner_join(demo_data, by = "wid") %>%
  select(wid,
         original_hm,
         gender, 
         marital, 
         parenthood,
         reflection_period,
         age, 
         country, 
         predicted_category, 
         text) %>%
  mutate(count = sapply(hm_data$text, wordcount)) %>%
  filter(gender %in% c("m", "f")) %>%
  filter(marital %in% c("single", "married")) %>%
  filter(parenthood %in% c("n", "y")) %>%
  filter(reflection_period %in% c("24h", "3m")) %>%
  mutate(reflection_period = fct_recode(reflection_period, 
                                        months_3 = "3m", hours_24 = "24h"))

Part 2 - Explore the participants. Who’s and what kind happy moments are we looking at?

## [1] 94506
## [1] 38707
## [1] 55799

With in the 94506 cleaned-up happy moments, 38707 of those belongs to women and 55799 belongs to men. The pie chart shows that most happy moments are gathered from the United States, followed by India, the rest of the world only contributes few entries for this particular data set. From the category plot we can see that most happy moments are in either the category of affection or achievement. It is not surprising to me those these two categories make up the majority of the happy moments. For example, other categories like, nature and exercise, may not appear as a happy moment to someone (like me) that does not enjoy going out or think exercise is weary. How about taking a look at the words in each categories and see what excactly what brings them happiness?

The tf-idf uses the frequency of words to determine how relevant those words are to a given document. I choose to look at the words that appears the most based on their categories. Since the majority of happy moments lays in affection and achievement category, I choose to look at them closely. The most word that occur the most for achievements are “won’,”job” and “bonus’. For affection, closely related people like”daughter”, “family” are the ones that got mentioned the most. I can totally related to the words and see how they got brought up the most.

Now, let’s take a look at the difference between men and women, since from personal experience what makes girls happy do not excites boys in the same way. Is there really a difference? if yes, how different?

Part 3 - Subset the data. When do women feel happy? And when do men?

From the histogram we can see, for women most happy moments occur in affection and for men they occur in achievement. This makes more sense why boys are more competitive than girls, as winning something (won has highest TF-IDF within achievement category) can bring more them more happiness.

Since affection is the most mentioned category within women, we take a closer look at the word frequency. With in the top 10 words occured except for “home” and “love” are all family members. Surrounding by people who love them, women feel happy the most. How about men?

On the other hand, for men, I chose to look at the word frequency for achievement, since that is their top category for happy moments. We can see that, except for “car”, “job”, and “money”, most words are associated with an action (eg. “bought”, “received”, etc.) Getting something meaningful done allow men to feel more happiness, compared to women, we focus less on our achievement when thinking about happy moments.

Does that mean all men need is work? Probably not, since for them, the second most category is also affection. Therefore, maybe we should look at who are the people that can make men feel happy.

Looking at both word clouds, we observe that friend got mentioned the most for both genders. Using embedding, we can see that friend is mostly associated “family”, “familyas”, and “fun”, while for men it is mostly associated with “fun”, “gap”, and “guard”. (To women probably friend is a lot more like a family member resulting in a high between those two words with “friend”.) Finally something in common! Similarity between friend and fun for women is 0.92 for women and 0.96 for men.

Next, let’s take a look at the kind of activity different genders do with friend that brings the most fun.

Part 5 - Take a closer look within the moments with friend

Except for special things like “birthday”, some activities that women enjoys with their friend are “surprise” and “celebrate”, and activities that men enjoys are “played” and “game”. There are also moments that both groups enjoy like “dinner” and “party”.

Using bigrams, the result also supports the same finding from above.

Part 6 - Difference based on region. Do we gain our happiness from same thing?

We know from the beginning that most entries are from USA, and since we are in the State, I’m also curious that whether the rest of the world and us share the source of happiness.

From the word clouds we can see that “friend” appears the most regard less of the region people are in. Those time spend with friend not only occur to us as happy moments, but also to the people in the other part of the world.
